\begin_layout Problem
(Attraction Effect and Choice Overload)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(60 points) (Too much choice/Choice overload and the Attraction Effect) Propose a model for consumer behavior that captures the following stylized facts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Choice Overload:
 Consumers are more likely to choose an outside option (that we equate in this problem to not choosing) when the size of the menu is too big.
 Hint:
 The choice set is 
\begin_inset Formula $X\cup\{o\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $o$
\end_inset

 is an outside option (not in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be finite.
 Menus are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup\{o\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq X$
\end_inset

,
 i.e.,
 the outside option is always available to the consumer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Attraction Effect:The 
\series bold
attraction effect
\series default
 is the observation that if we add an alternative to a menu,
 then some existing item becomes more attractive to the consumer and is picked by her.
 This introduced object is usually called the decoy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In formal terms,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-}\in X$
\end_inset

 be the decoy,
 so we are going to study its impact in the choice of the object of interest 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in X$
\end_inset

.
 The observation is the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\in c(A\cup\{b^{-}\})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\notin c(A),b\in A.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In probabilities,
 it means that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(b,A\cup\{b^{-}\})>p(b,A).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
You should describe with words what is the consumer choice algorithm.
 The model can be deterministic or stochastic,
 your choice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then you should describe what is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in your model and how that relates to some behavioral or bounded rationality feature we learned in class,
 and how it differs from utility maximization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally you should write the behavioral maximization problem and show how your new model predicts the two stylized facts.
 Also show,
 that the rational benchmark cannot deal with this models (neither random utility or deterministic utility maximization can predict the choice overload or attraction effect).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
You should try to explain the model to me in the best way you can,
 by using words,
 diagrams and examples.
 However,
 you should have also formality,
 make the effort to write down the model using math,
 this is the only way to get full credit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Describe what other testable implications your proposed model has.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
My model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a finite set of choices,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $o$
\end_inset

 a default,
 the grand choice set is 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{*}=X\cup\{o\}$
\end_inset

.
 The menus are 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}\subseteq2^{X^{*}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 has at least two elements 
\begin_inset Formula $|A|\geq2$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $o\in A$
\end_inset

 always.
 This default is always present.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer is endowed with a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X^{*}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(o)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer also has an attention index 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta:2^{X}\setminus\{o\}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that assigns how much attention does she pays to a bundle of items,
 e.g.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\{a,b,o\})=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\{a,o\})=\eta(\{b,o\})=1$
\end_inset

 means that the consumer pays more attention to 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 when they are together than alone.
 We let 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\emptyset)=-\infty$
\end_inset

,
 we also let 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(D)=-\infty$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $o\notin D.$
\end_inset

 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{A}(\{o\})=|A|$
\end_inset

 for every menu 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

.
 This means that for all other bundles that are not 
\begin_inset Formula $\{o\}$
\end_inset

 the attention index is always the same across menus,
 but for the default it changes with the cardinality.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{A}(D)=\eta(D)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $A\neq\{o\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This consumer is stochastic,
 so she will choose how much attention to pay to different alternatives solving the following problem.
 Attention is given as the probability of considering 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 for menu 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

.
 This is modelled as 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{A}\in\Delta(2^{A})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{A}^{*}=argmax_{m_{A}\in\Delta(2^{A})}\sum_{D\subseteq A}(m_{A}(D)\eta_{A}(D)-K(\eta_{A}(D))).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\eta(D))=\theta\eta_{A}(D)\log\eta_{A}(D)$
\end_inset

 is a convex cost function,
 in fact it is an entropy cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under this we get that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{A}(D)=\frac{exp(\theta\eta_{A}(D))}{\sum_{B\subseteq A}exp(\theta\eta_{A}(B))}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 we can compute the probability of choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathcal{A}:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{A}(a)=\sum_{D\subseteq A}1(u(a)>u(b)\forall b\in D\setminus\{a\})m_{A}(D).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the probability of choice is the expected frequency of times 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the best item among the consideration set 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is a random realization of the random consideration set distributed with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{A}\in\Delta(2^{A})$
\end_inset

,
 choice is random.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Choice overload
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{a,b,c\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)=3,u(b)=2,u(c)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u(o)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer picks 
\begin_inset Formula $o$
\end_inset

 only with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{A}(\{o\})$
\end_inset

,
 so we want 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{B}(\{o\})>m_{A}(\{o\})$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $B\supset A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need the following attention index 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\{a,o\})=\eta(\{b,o\})=\eta(\{c,o\})=1$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\{a,b,o\})=\eta(\{b,c,o\})=\eta(\{a,c,o\})=2$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\{a,b,c,o\})=3$
\end_inset

.
 We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{A}(\{o\})=|A|$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The default is easy to understand,
 so the attention index 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{A}(\{o\})$
\end_inset

 measures the opportunity cost of paying to attention to any item that is not the default.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plugging back the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{A}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{\{a,b,c,o\}}(\{o\})=\frac{exp(4\theta)}{10+exp(4\theta)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{\{a,b,o\}}(\{o\})=\frac{exp(3\theta)}{4+exp(3\theta)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choice overload happens when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=1$
\end_inset

 and other values:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename midtermfiguremodel.pdf
	lyxscale 150

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}-m_{2}=m_{\{a,b,c,o\}}(\{o\})-m_{\{a,b,o\}}(\{o\})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{B}(o)>\rho_{A}(o)$
\end_inset

,
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{a,b,c,o\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{a,b,o\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Attraction Effect
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{b,b^{-},c\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(b)=3$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(b^{-})=2,u(c)=1$
\end_inset

,
 also 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\{b,o\})=\eta(\{b^{-},o\})=\eta(\{c,o\})=1$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\{b,b^{-},o\})=3$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\{b,c,o\})=\eta(\{b^{-},c,o\})=2$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\{b,b^{-},c,o\})=5$
\end_inset

,
 as before we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{A}(\{o\})=|A|$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\{b,c,o\}}(b)<\rho_{\{b,b^{-},c,o\}}(b)$
\end_inset

,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $u(b)$
\end_inset

 is the best option it is not picked only because the agent does not pay attention to it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we have to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $y=m_{\{b,c,o\}}(\{b,o\})+m_{\{b,c,o\}}(\{b,c,o\})$
\end_inset

 is less than 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=m_{\{b,b^{-},c,o\}}(\{b,o\})+m_{\{b,b^{-},c,o\}}(\{b,c,o\})+m_{\{b,b^{-},c,o\}}(\{b,b^{-},o\})+m_{\{b,b^{-},c,o\}}(\{b,b^{-},c,o\})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=.146
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=.12
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{\{b,c,o\}}(b)=.12<\rho_{\{b,b^{-},o\}}(b)=.146
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Attraction effect is explained here by the complementarities of attention that makes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta(\{b,b^{-},o\})=3>\eta(\{b,o\})+\eta(\{b^{-},o\}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the calibration above Testable implication 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $|A|\geq|B|$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{A}(o)\geq\rho_{B}(o)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further testable implications.
 The main issue is when to stop,
 and that is when you need a characterization theorem.
 
\end_layout

